\begin_layout Section*
1.
 Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like all living organisms, the fruit fly uses sensory information to navigate
 its world.
 To a first approximation a fruit fly
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s behaviour in response to a sensory input can be described as a decision
 making process of approach or retreat.
 One such sense that the fly uses to decide whether to approach or retreat
 is the sense of smell, which is a well-studied function, employed to gather
 information about the environment, find food, mating partners, and detect
 dangerous conditions signaled by harmful odours.
 From the stage of larvae, flies are attracted to most odours, but also
 show innate aversion to specific odours (Niewalda et al., 2008).
 The behaviour of larvae depends on experience: if an odour is associated
 with a sweetened reward and another odour offers no reward the flies will
 show a preference for the rewarded odour in a binary choice test.
 However, if an odour is associated with a punishment such as high-concentration
 salt taste, larvae can be conditioned aversively to odours (Niewalda et
 al., 2008).
 Understanding how these memories of odours are generated and how they affect
 behaviour is an area of current research.
 Researchers are also beginning to understand how innate and learned olfactory
 behaviours interact with each other.
 However, until now there have been few computational driven approaches
 that have converted word models into mechanistic models that can explain
 the growing behavioural data and make predictions and testable hypotheses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Flies detect odours using olfactory receptor neurons (ORNs) housed in their
 antennae.
 The tuning of each OSN is determined by a single odorant receptor gene
 (Hallem & Carlson, 2006).
 Axons from the ORN expressing the same receptor always converge to the
 same site in the antennal lobe, which is a glomerulus.
 Their activity is picked up by inhibitory and excitatory projection neurons.
 Excitatory projection neurons (ePNs) deliver information to the calyces
 in the mushroom body while both inhibitory projection neurons (iPNs) and
 ePNs send information to the lateral horn which is a structure implicated
 in innate odour identification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1.1 The MB is the centre or associative learning in the fruit fly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mushroom bodies are symmetrical structures with each mushroom body being
 composed of 2,000 KCs.
 Lesion experiments and synaptic blocking of mushroom bodies output have
 shown that that the mushroom body plays a critical role in memory formation
 and retrieval (Heisenberg et al.
 1985).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each odour activates a unique subset of these neurons (Honegger, Campbell,
 & Turner, 2011).
 The dendrites of the KCs form the calyx of the MB, and their axons project
 anteriorly to form the stalk or peduncle before those axons terminate in
 one or more lobes, termed 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha',\beta'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobe (Krashes et al.
 2009).
 Each lobe contains a subset of the total number of KCs and they are believed
 to have unique roles in memory processing.
 In a previous study it has been shown by blocking different anatomical
 subdivisions of KCs, that the surface
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 neurons are needed during retrieval of aversive and appetitive memory whereas
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 core neurons, when blocked only affect appetitive memory (Perisse et al.,
 2013).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
1.1.1 The MB recurrent activity is critical for stabalizing odour memories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Olfactory representations in the mushroom bodies are modulated by anterior
 paired lateral (APL) and dorsal paired medial (DPM) neurons.
 The gap-junctional connection between DPM and APL could guarantee that
 excitation from DPM is balanced by a similar magnitude of inhibition from
 APL.
 The gap junction between the APL and DPM neurons has been shown to play
 an essential part for the mushroom body during memory formation, constituting
 a recurrent neural network (Pitman et al., 2011).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1.2 MBONs guide approach and retreat behaviours
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outputs from approximately 2,000 Kenyon cells of the mushroom body converge
 onto a population of only 34 mushroom body output neurons (MBONs), which
 fall into 21 anatomically distinct cell types (Aso et al., 2014).
 A simpler classification of the 32 MBONs can be according to the behaviour
 they bias towards.
 In a recent study it was shown that each MBON either promotes approach
 or retreat behaviour when a learned odour stimulus is paired with reinforcement
 (Aso et al.
 2014).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dendrites of MBONs is restricted to few DAN zones.
 For example in one MBON (M4
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'$
\end_inset

) that we have experimental data for, the axons from sugar rewarding dopaminergi
c neurons overlap with the dendrites of the MBON (David et.
 al 2015).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a recent study, MBONs were found to be broadly tuned, showing high levels
 of correlation between different MBON types (Hige, Aso, Rubin, & Turner,
 2015).
 In comparison to representation in the KCs, odours in the MBON were found
 to be much closer to one another.
 Odour representations in MBON of two groups of opposite valences were found
 to have the highest degree of seperability, thus suggesting that the MBON
 coding space is that of valence.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The M4 MBON exhibits bi-directional change in firing rate which makes it
 a prime candidate for modelling to test which hypothesis is best to explain
 experimental results from David et al.
 2015.
 Optogenetic activation of the M4 neurons drove avoidance behaviour.
 Blocking the M4 neuron converted odour approach into odour retreat in naïve
 flies (flies that had an innate repulsion to an odour without learning).
 Aversive training potentiated the M4 response whereas appetitive training
 depressed it.
 Conversely, aversive training depressed the MVP2 MBON which is believed
 to guide behaviour towards approach.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1.3 DAs convey reward and punishment signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dopaminergic neurons (DANS) are the most prevalent modulatory neurons that
 innervate the mushroom bodies.
 There are distinct dopaminergic neurons that provide positive and negative
 value signals.
 The two major clusters where most DANs reside are the PPL and the PAM clusters
 (Figure 1c).
 Positive reinforcement are provided by subsets of the approximately 100
 DANs in the PAM cluster (Burke et al., 2012), .
 They predominately innervate nearby zones in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,\beta',\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Negative reinforcement such as from electric shock or bitter substances
 appears to be conveyed by DANs housed in the PPL cluster.
 Each PPL DAN that innervates the mushroom bodies projects presynaptic terminals
 on the vertical lobes 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha’$
\end_inset

 or heel and surface of the peduncle (David Owald & Scott Waddell – in review).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
1.3.1 DAs convey reward and punishment signals in different areas of the mushroom
 body 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Distinct DANs convey the effects of sugar and water reward as opposed to
 the same neurons representing subjective value such as in the case of negative
 reinforcing DANs.
 The sugar and water responsive DANs project to unique zones on the MB lobes,
 thus suggesting that learning-related plasticity is represented in different
 places along the axon of an individual KC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is believed that since DANs reaches a subset of KCs axons, they modify
 KC output synapses onto MBONs in their respective zone.
 Thus water memories and sugar memories are predicted to have unique KC-MBON
 connections that represent them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
1.3.2 DA modulated learning changes odour drive to KC-MBON synapses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previously it has been shown that presynaptically expressed dDA1 receptors
 in KCs have affinity to dopamine which drives learning through plasticity.
 A hypothesis has been proposed by which learning modifies subsets of KC-MBON
 pathways which in naive flies are balanced.
 Appetitive responding DAs promotes odor approach by depressing odor drive
 to 'avoidance' MBONs and possibly by strenghtening approach pathways.
 Conversely, aversive responding DAs promotes depressing odour drive to
 'approach' MBONs (David Owald & Scott Waddell - in review).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous studies have shown that dopamine-drive plasticity occurs during
 reinforcement learning at the KC-MBON-DA junction.
 Aversive learning has been shown to depress odour-drive to the vertical
 lobe MBONs.
 Two competing theories could explain the effect of dopamine on the KC-MBON
 synapse.
 According to the first, dopamine always depresses the synapse.
 In this case potentiation would occur through the mechanism of lateral
 disinhibition from MBONs encoding opposite valences.
 This hypothesis is supported by anatomy that shows that generally DANs
 overlap with the dendrites of MBONs that bias towards In the second scenario,
 dopamine can exercise bi-directional control over the synapse leading to
 both potentiation and depression.
 This level of control would have computational benefits, allowing dopamine
 to 
\begin_inset Quotes els
\end_inset

fine-tune
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

 the synapse until it reaches a target value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have built models for both scenarios and in the next section we shall
 describe the constraints of the model and the predictions it makes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
1.4 Previous modelling attempts of olfactory learning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous modelling efforts of the fruit fly's olfactory circuit have mostly
 focused on the neurons implicated in olfactory processing up to the mushroom
 bodies output.
 This is because until three landmark studies this year (Hige & Turner,
 2015, Owald et al., 2015, Aso et al., 2014) relatively little was known about
 the properties of MBONs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous work (Luo et al., 2009) has modelled the transformation that occurs
 in the antennae lobe in an abstract rate-based model.
 The transformation takes into account lateral inhibition coming from local
 interneurons in the antennal lobe.
 This acts to decorrelate odour representations, which makes Kenyon Cell
 responses more selective to different odours.
 They show that sparseness in the mushroom body can be maintained with global
 inhibition a precise number of contacts between Projection Neurons and
 Kenyon Cells.
 This model has been used extensively to test hypotheses about other processes
 in the olfactory circuit ( e.g., Parnas et al, 2013).
 We will use this model as a starting point to explore the learning of appetitiv
e and aversive odor responses.
 We will add output neurons and neuromodulatory controls comprised of two
 families of neurons: octopamine and dopamine.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In one modelling effort the olfactory circuit was represented in its entirety,
 including with the ORNs in the antennae, the PNs and KCs and a single MBON.
 They tested a spiking model with plasticity takes occurring between KCs
 and MBONs and have show that the MBON can learn to distinguish between
 odours of opposite valences.
 They use a dopamine modulated STDP learning rule where pre-post spik pairs
 together with the presence of dopamine determines whether the weights will
 increase.
 However, current evidence shows that the presence of dopamine leads to
 depression.
 They also show their model can learn an odour mixture discrimination task
 where one half of the odour is paired with a negative reinforcement and
 another half is neutral (A-B).
 We have adapted the learning rule presented in this model and have added
 another MBON so that we can have a coding space for two valences represented
 by neurons that are in competition with each other.
\end_layout

