\begin_layout Section*
2.
 Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We shall now describe the methods used in this study.
 Experiments were performed by David Owald at the CNCB and motivated the
 simulations which were created by the author.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
2.1 Connectivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used experimental data that traces the connectivity between KCs and output
 neurons.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 neuron receives input from 200 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 lobe and 300 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 lobe.
 The MVP2 neuron receives input from 300 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobe and 200 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 lobe.
 The weights between KCs and MBONs were modelled using uniform random weights
 where all connection weights were set to a random value between 0nS and
 1nS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
2.2 MB Kenyon Cells model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We created a spiking model of the mushroom body valence learning circuit.
 The three main components that required modelling were the Kenyon Cells,
 the MBONs and DAs.
 To simulate an odour we first select randomly 200 neurons that are activated
 when an odour is shown, to ensure 10% sparseness (Andrew Lin et al.
 2014).
 We subsequently generated spike trains which are tuned to known statistics
 of KC spikes (Turner et al.
 2008).
 KC during spontaneous activity show very frugal spiking activity that averages
 around ~0.1 Hz.
 When an odour is shown, arandom sample of KCs fire at approximately 2 Hz
 with a large number of spikes occurring in the first 100 ms.
 To generate the KC spike train we use a Poisson inhomogeneous process described
 by the following equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\text{spike during \ensuremath{\Delta}t)}=e^{-r(t)\Delta t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where r(t) is a function that describes the firing rate profile of KCs.
\end_layout

